children.subject: 169 is not necessary if you have internship experience. I thought 186 was pretty useful all around, especially bc as a SWE a lot of your day to day work probably involves databases of some sort. Some of the main topics in 186 such as concurrency, data recovery do show up in 162, I would recommend possibly taking 186 before 162. Networking is kind of covered in 161, but I also have heard 168 is a chill/ez class. I have not taken 126 or 127 yet but plan to in the future, I heard the general advice is take 126 before, and then take 189 127 concurrently. 182 is neural networks, not really needed for general SWE work, but could be a good class to take if you are into ML and enjoyed 189.
Can you please give some feedback on 168? What is the workload like? How much coding is involved in the class?

<md>I just wanna say (as a former 168 TA) that 161 absolutely **does not** cover the content of 168 except for a small subset of TCP. If you want to learn about networking, 161 is the wrong class to take for that.</md>
im taking 161 162 ds100 this semester and i think it's doable! as long as you start hw/proj early you should be good
Is 161 and 162 together doable? for context Im taking 61c and 186 this semester and haven't found the schedule too bad.

history.content:
Done with all lower-division courses. I want to take 170, 162, 161, 186, 168, 189 for sure, but I want to be able to get a head start on learning real software engineering so I also want to take 169 and I heard its good to take  ee 127, ee 126 and 182 to get into ML which is something I am interested in looking into.

I heard 168 is kinda covered by 161, so I may not need it, but on the other hand it is said that 168 is a good class for industry, also how is the workload for 168?

I heard 169 is not well run, but I feel like I could still get something out of it that's directly applicable to my future job. Is cs 160 a better alternative?

I heard that 186 is not useful after taking 162? 

And then I hear people saying you won't really get ML without 127 and 126, some people say just take 126 or take 127 concurrently. Also, if I ever want to interview for a quant position I think 126 knowledge would be helpful, idk if they ask about 127 though.

And I don't know too much about 182.

I want to take these classes in a order that makes sense and I want to take the most necessary classes to be well-rounded and successful in SWE. Can you give me any advice on which classes to take my junior and senior year and maybe which classes I should reconsider on this list?
history.subject: I need help for my junior and Senior year schedule
